04191nam a22005415i 9780520914629DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19941994cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209146297 a10.1525/97805209146292doi  a(DE-B1597)648115  a(OCoLC)1419788501  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aPER0040002bisacsh1 aMarchetti, Gina, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRomance and the Yellow Peril :bRace, Sex, and Discursive Strategies in Hollywood Fiction /cGina Marchetti; ed. by Gina Marchetti. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[1994] 4cÂ©1994  a1 online resource (272 p.) :b30 b/w photographs  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tPreface -- t1. Introduction -- t2. The Rape Fantasy: The Cheat and Broken Blossoms -- t3. The Threat of Captivity: The Bitter Tea of General Yen and Shanghai Express -- t4. Passport Seductions: Lady of the Tropics -- t5. The Scream of the Butterfly: Madame Butterfly, China Gate, and "The Lady from Yesterday" -- t6. White Knights in Hong Kong: Love Is a Many-Splendored Thing and The World of Suzie Wong -- t7. Tragic and Transcendent Love: Sayonara and The Crimson Kimono -- t8. Japanese War Brides: Domesticity and Assimilation in Japanese War Bride and Bridge to the Sun -- t9. The Return of the Butterfly: The Geisha Masquerade in My Geisha and "An American Geisha" -- t10. Conclusion: The Postmodern Spectacle of Race and Romance in Year of the Dragon -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHollywood films about Asians and interracial sexuality are the focus of Gina Marchetti's provocative new work. While miscegenation might seem an unlikely theme for Hollywood, Marchetti shows how fantasy-dramas of interracial rape, lynching, tragic love, and model marriage are powerfully evident in American cinema.The author begins with a discussion of D. W. Griffith's Broken Blossoms, then considers later films such as Shanghai Express, Madame Butterfly, and the recurring geisha movies. She also includes some fascinating "forgotten" films that have been overlooked by critics until now.Marchetti brings the theoretical perspective of recent writing on race, ethnicity, and gender to her analyses of film and television and argues persuasively that these media help to perpetuate social and racial inequality in America. Noting how social norms and taboos have been simultaneously set and broken by Hollywood filmmakers, she discusses the "orientalist" tensions underlying the construction of American cultural identity. Her book will be certain to interest readers in film, Asian, women's, and cultural studies.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aFilm. 4aGeneral. 4aPerforming Arts. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / General.2bisacsh1 aMarchetti, Gina, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052008495740uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052091462940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520914629423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520914629/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles